      "message": "Also, I know Gunnar can find this, but for documentation to anyone else that wants to help with this effort, this is where bmcweb currently maps inventory items to a sensor:\n\nhttps://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/8615915cc51a468c1c0b6eabb684616d0f2abe0f/redfish-core/lib/chassis.hpp#L480\n\nA redfish \"Chassis\" can be of type Item.Board or Item.Chassis, so saying that the all_sensors-\u003echassis association is only used for Item.Chassis isn\u0027t correct.\n\nI\u0027d also mention that the documentation pointed out earlier has an all_sensors association: https://github.com/openbmc/docs/blob/80f55a589d474e40cef0f9b6ee728098b8da159d/architecture/sensor-architecture.md?plain\u003d1#L66\n\nWhen this association was first made \"chassis\" was used in the redfish terms of \"Contains things\", not in the sense of \"Is a piece of sheet metal that has stuff in it\".  A fan functionally contains its sensors, so a fan sensor would be associated with the fan item.\n\nThe options I see are:\n1. What this patchset proposes, use the associations inconsistently, with the only example being hardcoded examples in an IBM platform, and keep all_sensors in the sensor schema, while using sensors association in the ThermalSubsystem schema.\n2. Change the existing all_sensors-\u003echassis associations to use sensors, so we\u0027re consistent.  This breaks everyone that implemented a downstream sensor, which at this point we might not care about, but we should consider the implications on rebasing.\n3. use the all_sensors association, make a minor change to one ibm platform to change a \"sensor\" association to \"all_sensors\" and be done with it.\n\n\nFWIW, I think 3 is the easiest.  1 I\u0027m not really interested in supporting.  We\u0027ve been burned too many times using DBus inconsistently.  2 would be viable, but someone would have to put up the patches and do the work, and I don\u0027t think breaking everyone downstream is worthwhile for what amounts to a difference in naming.",
